-- HDFC Bank, ICICI Bank, Shoppers Stop, Nestle India: India Equity Preview
-- Unni Krishnan
-- 2010-07-01T03:10:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-01/hdfc-bank-icici-bank-shoppers-stop-nestle-india-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 166.81, or 1 percent, to 17,700.90. The S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange rose 1.1 percent to
5,312.50. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.8 percent to 2,248.06.
SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index Futures for July delivery lost 1.1 to
5,260 at 10:39 a.m. in Singapore.  
 Banks:  ICICI Bank Ltd.  (ICICIBC IN): India’s largest non-
state lender set its base rate at 7.5 percent, effective from
July 1, it said in a statement. Rival  HDFC Bank Ltd . (HDFCB IN)
set its rate at 7.25 percent. ICICI Bank rose 1.6 percent to
861.7 rupees. HDFC Bank climbed 0.8 percent to 1,919 rupees.  
 Sugar stocks: The progress of India monsoon has stalled,
which may reduce sugar and rice crops in the northern states,
the Hindustan Times reported, citing an official in the weather
office that it didn’t identify. The monsoon, 21 percent
deficient in the week to June 23, is unlikely to progress to
India rice-growing areas before July 4, according to the report.  
 Balrampur Chini Mills Ltd.  (BRCM IN), the nation’s second-
biggest mill, gained 2.1 percent to 84.45 rupees.  Shree Renuka
Sugars Ltd.  (SHRS IN), India’s biggest refiner, lost 1.3 percent
to 67.85 rupees.  Bajaj Hindusthan Ltd.  (BJH IN), India’s biggest
sugar maker, declined 0.1 percent to 116.95 rupees.  
 Indian Oil Corp.  (IOCL IN): India’s second-largest refiner
will increase jet fuel prices to 42,808.92 rupees a kiloliter
from 41,469.45 rupees a kiloliter in Mumbai starting today,
according to the company’s website. The stock rose 2.5 percent
to 403.1 rupees.  
 Nestle India Ltd.  (NEST IN): The unit of the world’s
biggest food company plans to buy a local company to expand its
business and will announce the acquisition “sooner than
later,” Chairman and Managing Director  Antonio Helio Waszyk 
said. Nestle fell 0.6 percent to 2,879.55 rupees.  
 NHPC Ltd.  (NHPC IN): India’s biggest hydroelectric power
producer was raised to “hold” from “reduce” by BNP Paribas
analyst  Girish Nair , who said the stock’s underperformance
prices in the company’s execution delays. The analyst raised his
share-price estimate to 32 rupees from 29 rupees. The shares
gained 3.5 percent to 31.4 rupees.  
 NMDC Ltd.  (NMDC IN): Asia’s third-largest iron ore producer
may raise prices of fines by 15 percent to about 3,335 rupees
per metric ton in the three months to September, S. Thiagarajan,
director finance at the company, said in a phone interview. The
stock fell 0.3 percent to 265.55 rupees.  
 Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd.  (MM IN): India’s largest maker of
sport-utility vehicles and tractors is in talks with Boeing Co.
to buy a plant in Australia, Business Standard reported, without
saying where it got the information. Mumbai-based Mahindra may
buy either a components or aircraft-manufacturing plant,
according to the report. The shares increased 2.2 percent to
627.35 rupees.  
 Parabolic Drugs Ltd.  (PDL IN): The maker of pharmaceutical
ingredients commences trading today. The company raised 2
billion rupees ($43 million) selling 2.03 million shares to the
public at 75 rupees a piece.  
 Reliance Power Ltd.  (RPWR IN): The U.S. Export-Import Bank
will reconsider its rejection of a loan guarantee for  Bucyrus
International Inc.  so it can sell coal-mining equipment for a
power project being developed by Reliance Power, controlled by
billionaire  Anil Ambani .  
 The bank acted after Democratic lawmakers in Wisconsin,
where Bucyrus is based, appealed the rejection last week of $560
million in financing on environmental grounds. Reliance told the
bank it may buy U.S. equipment for a renewable energy project,
bank Chairman  Fred Hochberg  said in a letter. Reliance Power
climbed 1.1 percent to 171.4 rupees.  
 Shoppers Stop Ltd.  (SHOP IN): India’s second-largest
publicly traded retailer completed the purchase of a 32 percent
stake in Hypercity Retail (India) Ltd., raising its holdings to
51 percent, it said in a statement on the Bombay Stock Exchange.
Shoppers Stop rose 6.9 percent to 568.45 rupees.  
 Tata Power Ltd.  (TPWR IN): India’s largest non-state
generator will raise $300 million by selling stakes in two units
that own Indonesian coal mines to Olympus Capital Holdings Asia
to pay for securing more supplies and reduce debt. The stock
rose 0.4 percent to 1,308.35 rupees.  
